Project: Investigate TMDb movie database¶

Table of Contents¶

  • Introduction
  • Data Wrangling
  • Exploratory Data Analysis
  • Conclusions

Introduction¶

Welcome to TMDb movie database investigation! We're going to explore a valuable data set which contains data for over 10,000 movies collected from The Movie Database (TMDb), the data are going to need some cleaning and tidiness before we can start but still it's quite the find and all credit goes to Kaggle and Udacity.

There are tons of options to handle the investigation so statistically speaking I can't mess this up even if I tried (famous last words before messing up). I am deeply intrested in finding out what national treasure of an actor stared most in movies, also what about the distribution of movies genres ? the movies count of each year ? are movies getting shorter ? and finally can we find out the traits of successful movies ?

Research Questions¶

  • 1: Which movie star landed the leading role most ?
  • 2: What is the distribution of movies genres ?
  • 3: How many movies are released every year ?
  • 4: How long are movies every year ?
  • 5: What are the traits associated with successful movies ?

Data Wrangling¶

Let's load in the data, check for cleanliness, and then trim and clean the data set for analysis. I will make sure to document my steps carefully and justify my cleaning decisions.

Question 3: How many movies are released every year ?¶

In [13]:
# Define a function to line plot an aggregate vs years
def line_plot(style, aggregate, xticks, yticks, title, xlabel, ylabel, color):
    """ Line plot chart using matplotlib’s built-in styles
    
    INPUTS:
    style: matplotlib built in styles
    aggregate: the plotted aggregate grouped by release_year
    xticks: x-axis ticks
    yticks: y-axis ticks
    title: chart title
    xlabel: x-axis label
    ylabel: y-axis label
    color: labels colors
    
    OUTPUTS:
    Line chart with a column aggregate on the x-axis and release years on y-axis
    """
    plt.style.use(style)
    aggregate.plot(figsize=(10,5))
    plt.xticks(xticks,xticks)
    plt.yticks(yticks)
    plt.title(title, fontsize= 25, color= color)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel, fontsize= 18, color= color)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel, fontsize= 18, color= color)
    return plt.show()
In [14]:
# Aggregate released movies per year
yearly_releases = df.groupby('release_year')['original_title'].count()

# Reset plot style
plt.style.use('default')
# Call line plot function to plot the chart
line_plot('seaborn-whitegrid', 
          yearly_releases, np.arange(1955,2016,5), np.arange(0,800,50), 
          'Movies Releases per Year', 'Years', 'Movies Count','maroon')

Seems like movies count has been going steadily up untill 2000, from then the count spiked up. Is movies industry becoming more profitable and in demand lately ?¶

In [22]:
# Define a function to scatter plot two columns
def scatter_plot(style, col_1, col_2, title, xlabel, ylabel, color):
    """ Scatter plot using matplotlib’s built-in styles
    
    INPUTS:
    style: matplotlib built in styles
    col_1: x-axis values
    col_2: y-axis values
    title: chart title
    xlabel: x-axis label
    ylabel: y-axis label
    color: labels colors
    
    OUTPUTS:
    Scatter plot the correlation between two columns
    """
    plt.style.use(style)
    plt.scatter(x= col_1 , y= col_2)
    plt.title(title, fontsize= 25, color= color)
    plt.xlabel(xlabel, fontsize= 18, color= color)
    plt.ylabel(ylabel, fontsize= 18, color= color)
    return plt.show()

Conclusions¶

  • On average a top 10 lead actor stars in 37 movies, Nicolas Cage outlies the average by 13 movies.

  • The top 2 genres (31.6%) make one third of movies count while the top 4 genres (51.2%) make half.

  • Movies count is on the rise since the 60s and spiked up from the 00s.

  • Movies runtime slowly shortens with time.

  • Top Movies with at least 300% profit have strong correlation between revenue, budget and vote count.

Limitations¶

  • More than half of the data contains zero values in either budget or revenue.

  • Popularity column isn't properly explained and it's scale is unknown.

  • Columns with names aren't well formatted.
